<subSubSection id="3CD75DE6FFCBFFBAFF34E65DFDC639B9" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="461" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="74720E6DFFCBFFBCFF34E65DFF273DAD" blockId="2.[160,1156,332,1710]" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFF34E65DFEDE3E55" bold="true" box="[160,282,332,358]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Species of this group have dusky wings with dark veins and pterostigma. Females are recognised by the pointed fourth tooth of the mandible (
<figureCitation id="ECF612E8FFCBFFBCFC5AE67EFBE33EBB" box="[974,1063,367,392]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1340,1363]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetId="figure-45@3.[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Megachile leucografa, female, clypeus and mandibles; (b) M. leucografa, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area, tuft of hairs on inner surface of mandible (‘t’), and oblique row of hairs on under surface of femur (‘r’); (c) M. obscurior, male, ventral view showing glabrous, rugose hypostomal area; (d) M. rancaguensis, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area; (e) M. leucografa, female, hind tarsus; lines indicate measurements of length and width of basitarsus; (f) M. obscurior, male, dorsal view of apical metasomal terga. Scale bars: a, e = 0.5 mm; b–d, f = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475468" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475468/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(a)), the apical margin of the clypeus with a median smooth emargination (
<figureCitation id="ECF612E8FFCBFFBCFC09E683FC313E98" box="[925,1013,402,427]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1340,1363]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetId="figure-45@3.[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Megachile leucografa, female, clypeus and mandibles; (b) M. leucografa, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area, tuft of hairs on inner surface of mandible (‘t’), and oblique row of hairs on under surface of femur (‘r’); (c) M. obscurior, male, ventral view showing glabrous, rugose hypostomal area; (d) M. rancaguensis, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area; (e) M. leucografa, female, hind tarsus; lines indicate measurements of length and width of basitarsus; (f) M. obscurior, male, dorsal view of apical metasomal terga. Scale bars: a, e = 0.5 mm; b–d, f = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475468" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475468/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(a)), and the broad hind basitarsus (
<figureCitation id="ECF612E8FFCBFFBCFE0FE6A4FE343EFD" box="[411,496,437,462]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1340,1363]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetId="figure-45@3.[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Megachile leucografa, female, clypeus and mandibles; (b) M. leucografa, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area, tuft of hairs on inner surface of mandible (‘t’), and oblique row of hairs on under surface of femur (‘r’); (c) M. obscurior, male, ventral view showing glabrous, rugose hypostomal area; (d) M. rancaguensis, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area; (e) M. leucografa, female, hind tarsus; lines indicate measurements of length and width of basitarsus; (f) M. obscurior, male, dorsal view of apical metasomal terga. Scale bars: a, e = 0.5 mm; b–d, f = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475468" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475468/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(e)). Males are distinguished by the basal tuft of long, dense hairs on the inner surface of the mandible (on the condylar interspace, 
<figureCitation id="ECF612E8FFCBFFBCFC23E6C6FBC83EC3" box="[951,1036,471,496]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1340,1363]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetId="figure-45@3.[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Megachile leucografa, female, clypeus and mandibles; (b) M. leucografa, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area, tuft of hairs on inner surface of mandible (‘t’), and oblique row of hairs on under surface of femur (‘r’); (c) M. obscurior, male, ventral view showing glabrous, rugose hypostomal area; (d) M. rancaguensis, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area; (e) M. leucografa, female, hind tarsus; lines indicate measurements of length and width of basitarsus; (f) M. obscurior, male, dorsal view of apical metasomal terga. Scale bars: a, e = 0.5 mm; b–d, f = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475468" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475468/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(b–d)), the emarginate and spineless preapical carina of T6 (
<figureCitation id="ECF612E8FFCBFFBCFD71E6EBFC863D20" box="[741,834,506,531]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1340,1363]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetId="figure-45@3.[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Megachile leucografa, female, clypeus and mandibles; (b) M. leucografa, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area, tuft of hairs on inner surface of mandible (‘t’), and oblique row of hairs on under surface of femur (‘r’); (c) M. obscurior, male, ventral view showing glabrous, rugose hypostomal area; (d) M. rancaguensis, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area; (e) M. leucografa, female, hind tarsus; lines indicate measurements of length and width of basitarsus; (f) M. obscurior, male, dorsal view of apical metasomal terga. Scale bars: a, e = 0.5 mm; b–d, f = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475468" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475468/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(f)), the flattened, yellowish foretarsus with a large fringe of hairs and short, broad basitarsus (
<figureCitation id="ECF612E8FFCBFFBCFC3DE50CFBCD3D05" box="[937,1033,541,566]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1250,1273]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1218]" captionTargetId="figure-112@4.[163,1153,142,1218]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Lateral habitus of Megachile species of the M. leucografa group: (a). M. leucografa, female; (b) M. leucografa, male; (c). M. obscurior, female holotype; (d) M. obscurior, male; (e) M. rancaguensis, female holotype; (f) M. rancaguensis, male. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475470" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475470/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(b,d,f)), the broad translucent separation area of S5 (
<figureCitation id="ECF612E8FFCBFFBCFDE5E52EFD0A3D6B" box="[625,718,575,600]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="5.[160,225,1606,1629]" captionTargetBox="[162,1144,1218,1575]" captionTargetId="figure-49@5.[162,1152,1218,1575]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 4. Megachile obscurior, male: (a) S5; (b) S6; (c) S8; (d) genital capsule, ventral view. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475474" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475474/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(a); and 
<bibRefCitation id="105C739CFFCBFFBCFCB8E52EFC083D6B" author="Durante SP" box="[812,972,575,600]" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" pagination="41 - 44" refId="ref6767" refString="Durante SP. 1994. Aportes al conocimiento de Chrysosarus (Dactylomegachile) trochantina (Vachal 1909) comb. nov. (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae). Neotropica. 40 (103 - 104): 41 - 44." type="journal article" year="1994">Durante (1994</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 4), and the broad, rounded apical lobes of the postgradular area of S6 (
<figureCitation id="ECF612E8FFCBFFBCFCBAE573FC4C3D48" box="[814,904,610,635]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="5.[160,225,1606,1629]" captionTargetBox="[162,1144,1218,1575]" captionTargetId="figure-49@5.[162,1152,1218,1575]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 4. Megachile obscurior, male: (a) S5; (b) S6; (c) S8; (d) genital capsule, ventral view. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475474" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475474/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(b); and 
<bibRefCitation id="105C739CFFCBFFBCFC75E573FBBA3D48" author="Durante SP" box="[993,1150,610,635]" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" pagination="41 - 44" refId="ref6767" refString="Durante SP. 1994. Aportes al conocimiento de Chrysosarus (Dactylomegachile) trochantina (Vachal 1909) comb. nov. (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae). Neotropica. 40 (103 - 104): 41 - 44." type="journal article" year="1994">Durante (1994</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 5).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="74720E6DFFCBFFBCFF54E5B6FCB33C1B" blockId="2.[160,1156,332,1710]" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">
Species of this group share many characters with those species that have been included in 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFEB1E5DBFE233DD0" box="[293,487,714,739]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Chrysosarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="457" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Dactylomegachile">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFEB1E5DBFE233DD0" box="[293,487,714,739]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Dactylomegachile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but they also share some features with the amber-winged species that have been included in 
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFDAFE5FCFC8A3C35" box="[571,846,749,774]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFDAFE5FCFD783C35" box="[571,700,749,774]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Chrysosarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">Chrysosarus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="5D8A6F04FFCBFFBCFD52E5FCFC8A3C35" box="[710,846,749,774]" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" sensu="stricto">sensu stricto</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFCCBE5FCFC5F3C35" box="[863,923,749,774]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="105C739CFFCBFFBCFC31E5FCFB803C35" author="Mitchell TB" box="[933,1092,749,774]" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" pagination="656 - 671" refId="ref7375" refString="Mitchell TB. 1943. On the classification of neotropical Megachile (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae). Ann Entomol Soc Am. 36 (4): 656 - 671. doi: 10.1093 / aesa / 36.4.656." type="journal article" year="1943">Mitchell, 1943</bibRefCitation>
). The diagnostic features of the 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFE5CE41EFDFF3C1B" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1908" box="[456,571,783,808]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucografa">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFE5CE41EFDFF3C1B" box="[456,571,783,808]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">leucografa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group are discussed below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="74720E6DFFCBFFBCFF54E423FEC03B28" blockId="2.[160,1156,332,1710]" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">
Among species that have been included in 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFD36E423FCA03C78" box="[674,868,818,843]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Chrysosarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="457" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Dactylomegachile">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFD36E423FCA03C78" box="[674,868,818,843]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Dactylomegachile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the pointed fourth tooth of the female mandible occurs only in the 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFDE1E444FD2C3C5D" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1908" box="[629,744,853,878]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucografa">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFDE1E444FD2C3C5D" box="[629,744,853,878]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">leucografa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, while other species with dark veins and pterostigma have a distinctly incised, or less frequently truncate, fourth tooth. A pointed fourth tooth, on the contrary, can be found among species of 
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFC54E48BFF263CE5" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFC54E48BFB853C80" box="[960,1089,922,947]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Chrysosarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">Chrysosarus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="5D8A6F04FFCBFFBCFBD3E48BFF263CE5" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" sensu="stricto">sensu stricto</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, as for example in 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFE2EE4ACFDB33CE5" authorityName="Schrottky" authorityYear="1908" box="[442,631,957,982]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catamarcensis">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFE2EE4ACFDB33CE5" box="[442,631,957,982]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">M. catamarcensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although amber-winged species usually have a broadly truncate, low fourth tooth (which in some specimens may appear pointed due to wear).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="74720E6DFFCBFFBCFF54E334FE453A60" blockId="2.[160,1156,332,1710]" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">
The broad hind basitarsus of the female is characteristic of the 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFC2BE334FBF63B0D" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1908" box="[959,1074,1061,1086]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucografa">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFC2BE334FBF63B0D" box="[959,1074,1061,1086]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">leucografa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (2.5–2.7× as long as its maximum width in lateral view, 
<figureCitation id="ECF612E8FFCBFFBCFC80E356FCA83B53" box="[788,876,1095,1120]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1340,1363]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetId="figure-45@3.[163,1153,142,1308]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. (a) Megachile leucografa, female, clypeus and mandibles; (b) M. leucografa, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area, tuft of hairs on inner surface of mandible (‘t’), and oblique row of hairs on under surface of femur (‘r’); (c) M. obscurior, male, ventral view showing glabrous, rugose hypostomal area; (d) M. rancaguensis, male, ventral view showing pilose hypostomal area; (e) M. leucografa, female, hind tarsus; lines indicate measurements of length and width of basitarsus; (f) M. obscurior, male, dorsal view of apical metasomal terga. Scale bars: a, e = 0.5 mm; b–d, f = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475468" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475468/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(e)), and approaches the condition seen in species with amber wings (2.7–2.8×, in species such as 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFC70E37BFB473BB0" authorityName="Schrottky" authorityYear="1909" box="[996,1155,1130,1155]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guaranitica">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFC70E37BFB473BB0" box="[996,1155,1130,1155]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">M. guaranitica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFF41E39CFE913B95" authorityName="Mitchell" authorityYear="1930" box="[213,341,1165,1190]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="concava">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFF41E39CFE913B95" box="[213,341,1165,1190]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">M. concava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In species with dark veins and pterostigma, other than those of the 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFF34E3BEFED73BFB" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1908" box="[160,275,1199,1224]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucografa">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFF34E3BEFED73BFB" box="[160,275,1199,1224]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">leucografa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, the female hind basitarsus is slender, varying from 3.1–3.2× (in species such as 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFE96E3C3FE0E3BD8" authority="Vachal" authorityName="Vachal" authorityYear="1908" box="[258,458,1234,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vagata">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFE96E3C3FEB03BD8" box="[258,372,1234,1259]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">M. vagata</emphasis>
Vachal
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFD9FE3C3FCEE3BD8" authority="Holmberg" authorityName="Holmberg" authorityYear="1886" box="[523,810,1234,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ctenophora">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFD9FE3C3FD693BD8" box="[523,685,1234,1259]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">M. ctenophora</emphasis>
Holmberg
</taxonomicName>
) to 3.35× as long as wide in 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFF34E3E4FEC33A3D" authorityName="Vachal" authorityYear="1908" box="[160,263,1269,1294]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="infima">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFF34E3E4FEC33A3D" box="[160,263,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">M. infima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Another characteristic of the 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFDCBE3E4FD163A3D" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1908" box="[607,722,1269,1294]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucografa">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFDCBE3E4FD163A3D" box="[607,722,1269,1294]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">leucografa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is the medially smooth, weakly concave apical margin of the female clypeus, which is denticulate in most species of the 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFF34E22BFEE53A60" box="[160,289,1338,1363]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Chrysosarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFF34E22BFEE53A60" box="[160,289,1338,1363]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">Chrysosarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lineage.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="74720E6DFFCBFFBCFF54E24CFEA83910" blockId="2.[160,1156,332,1710]" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">
Regarding the males, the basal tuft of hairs on the inner surface of the mandible, not accompanied by any projection, is unique to the 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFD42E26EFC8E3AAB" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1908" box="[726,842,1407,1432]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucografa">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFD42E26EFC8E3AAB" box="[726,842,1407,1432]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">leucografa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group among species with dark wings, but it occurs in some of those species with amber wings (e.g. in 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFF34E2D4FE5E3AED" authority="Mitchell" authorityName="Mitchell" authorityYear="1929" box="[160,410,1477,1502]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tapytensis">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFF34E2D4FEF03AED" box="[160,308,1477,1502]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">M. tapytensis</emphasis>
Mitchell
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFE48E2D4FD033AED" authority="Mitchell" authorityName="Mitchell" authorityYear="1930" box="[476,711,1477,1502]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="concava">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFE48E2D4FD993AED" box="[476,605,1477,1502]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">M. concava</emphasis>
Mitchell
</taxonomicName>
). Usually, amber-winged species have profuse pilosity on the condylar interspace of the mandible, while dark-winged species have sparse hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="74720E6DFFCBFFBDFF54E13CFDC939AD" blockId="2.[160,1156,332,1710]" lastBlockId="3.[160,1156,1599,1694]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="460" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">
Features shared by species of the 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCBFFBCFD17E13CFD3D3975" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1908" box="[643,761,1581,1606]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="459" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucografa">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCBFFBCFD17E13CFD3D3975" box="[643,761,1581,1606]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="459">leucografa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group with other dark-winged species are the presence of ferruginous bristles on the nearly glabrous anterior surface of the forecoxa of the male, and the presence of a distinct angle on the lower margin of the male mandible. The preapical carina of T6 is unarmed and emarginate in the 
<taxonomicName id="B3CD75EEFFCAFFBDFEEDE12EFE2B396B" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1908" box="[377,495,1599,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="460" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucografa">
<emphasis id="46B9D27FFFCAFFBDFEEDE12EFE2B396B" box="[377,495,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="460">leucografa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, but a similar carina can be found among dark as well as among amber-winged species, since the carina of T6 is variable in shape and ornamentation in both groups.
</paragraph>
<caption id="20B25EE5FFCAFFBDFF34E22DFB403AD6" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5475468" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5475468" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5475468/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="460" startId="3.[160,225,1340,1363]" targetBox="[163,1153,142,1308]" targetPageId="3">
